The paper deals with planning in multi-agent settings, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The incorporation of agent models and Bayesian updates suggests a game-theoretic approach, which is a subfield of AI that deals with decision making in interactive settings (cs.GT). The use of belief states and the focus on autonomy of agents suggests a focus on multi-agent systems (cs.MA). The mention of value iteration and piece-wise linearity and convexity of value functions suggests a connection to robotics (cs.RO) and control systems (cs.SY).
